      "If the Upaniṣads were Hinduism's philosophical breakthrough, the Epic period was its dramatic flowering. In this era, the abstract truths of the Upaniṣads were woven into stories so powerful, so rich in human complexity, that they became the living scripture of an entire civilization.",
      "The Mahābhārata — attributed to the sage Vyāsa — grew over centuries into the longest poem in world literature: roughly 100,000 verses, seven times the combined length of the Iliad and Odyssey. At its narrative heart is the fratricidal war between the Pāṇḍavas and Kauravas, but it is far more than a war story. It is an encyclopaedia of dharma, containing within it the Bhagavad Gītā, the teachings of Bhīṣma on statecraft and ethics, cosmological myths, love stories, fables, and some of the most morally complex situations ever depicted in literature.",
